David Andrew Laws here, Artistic Director of Hamlet Isn‚Äôt Dead and fellow Great British Bake Off enthusiast.

The HID community has been so lucky this year in so many ways. We‚Äôve increased our administration, expanded our Resident Acting Company, and found new and inventive ways to bring quality HIDiocy to our online community. We have also had, as has the entire world, our share of setbacks (to put it lightly).¬†

As we continue to navigate this season, we‚Äôre feeling the burn, and we know you are too. The spirit is willing, but the bandwidth is finite, as it were. As such, we will be postponing our main stage productions for the foreseeable future. The plan is for these to return once we are able to perform them live, whether that happens as a result of theatrical spaces reopening safely or once the weather warms up and circumstances permit outdoor performances.¬†

We will continue to produce as much online content as we can. Our Contemporaries of Color series continues in late January with a piece based on Phillis Wheatley‚Äôs Poems on Various Subjects, Religious and Moral, and in February with the Turkish shadow puppetry play Kanli Kavak (The Bloody Poplar). We will also continue meeting with the HIDRAC, and they‚Äôll be bringing you light and love on our channel and through their interactions with other companies and each other.¬†

The arts always needs your support, whether you‚Äôre an active participant in a community or a long-distance admirer, and obviously that need now is more than ever. We hope you‚Äôre able to continue your support of us and our work as we offer pay-what-you-can ticketing for these next events and work to find the best way to bring you our signature brand of joyful, immediate theatre with as few compromises as possible.¬†

This holiday season will be uniquely difficult, so know that we will still be here, providing joy and distraction via our social media, looking back at seasons past, and looking forward to a brighter future. Stay safe, stay sane, and we look forward to reveling with you as we wind our way through the rest of the Shakespearean canon as soon as we can celebrate doing so together.¬†

Best,
David Andrew Laws
and the HID staff

We're so excited to invite you all to the second work in our Contemporaries of Color series: "Words on the Water: a Celebration of Phillis Wheatley" (ticket link in our bio)!

Hamlet Isn't Dead partners with guest director & deviser DeMone Seraphin to create this unique online performance. Based on her book, Poems on Various Subjects, Religious and Moral, this piece explores the important work and life of America's first Black poet.

Enjoy music, atmosphere, and a story too-rarely told with Words on the Water, a two-nights-only event.

Thank you for your patience. It is important to us that we not just talk the talk, but that we set ourselves up to walk the walk as well. We've been listening, brainstorming, and outlining actionable goals for ourselves. Here is the result of that.

We want to do better. We want Hamlet Isn't Dead to be better. And we can only do that through change and togetherness.

We are genuinely excited to pursue these goals. It feels like a fresh start for our seven-year-old company. We look forward to continued conversations, new friends, and bigger, louder celebrations of every shade of skin and walk of life under the sun.

Thank you for your support, your love, and your commitment to these goals alongside us, whether you're a  part of our community onstage, backstage, from the audience, or from afar. We know that this is only the beginning, and we are thrilled to see the outcome of these changes this year and far into the future.

All the best,
Hamlet Isn't Dead
.
.

Introducing our Hamlet(s) and Ophelia(s)!
Artistic Director David Andrew Laws and long-time HID stalwart Megan Greener!
.
David Andrew Laws is the co-founder and Artistic Director of Hamlet Isn't Dead. In addition to directing many HID shows, he has performed in a handful, including turns as Petruchio, Buckingham, Costard, and Nick Bottom. Last year he joined the hit off-broadway show DRUNK SHAKESPEARE, where he has done over 70 performances as Macbeth.
.
Megan Greener joined Hamlet Isn't Dead in its second year and has played many of Shakespeare's juiciest roles with us. There's nothing new to her playing roles traditionally written for men, as she brought the house down as both the towering King Henry V and as the hilarious Dogberry in last year's Much Ado About Nothing.
.
Both performers are already hard at work in preliminary workshops for the show, and we can't wait for you to see their work. You can find the casting schedule on eventbrite when you buy your tickets, make sure to catch them both!
.
Tickets available now at www.hidham.eventbrite.com. Get them before they blench!
.
For more info, visit www.hamletisntdead.com

Heya #HIDiots, 
After an incredibly full 24/25 season, this year, Hamlet Isn‚Äôt Dead is taking a breath. Instead of diving straight into a mainstage, we‚Äôre focusing on what will make us stronger in the long run: building up our ensemble, sharpening our structure, and expanding the education and community programs that keep us connected. It‚Äôs a chance to grow our artistry through workshops, strengthen our funding through grants and donor support, and get clear on our vision for what HID is becoming. By slowing down now, we‚Äôre setting ourselves up for productions that are more sustainable, more impactful, and truer to our mission of creating the best Shakespeare experiences for our audiences. In the meantime, watch this space for how we are filling our development year and what we are planning to bring to the stage next!

Love,

Text reads: Hamlet Isn't Dead's Pericles. Why no boys allowed? Quote from Tina Packer's book, Women of Will: "It has taken hundreds of years for women‚Äôs voices to be heard and affect the course of human events. In order for the world to find its healthy balance, all women‚Äôs voices need to be heard." End quote. Text continues: We have taken that sentiment and included all marginalized genders, not just women, in this reimagining of Pericles. Hamlet Isn't Dead has a long history of non-male interpretations, like in the 2017 production of Henry the fifth, the 2018 production of As You Like It, and the 2019 production of Troilus and Cressida. Quote from Olivia Basile, who plays Pericles, "When you're someone in a body or a gender that is marginalized, you're never thinking Pericles is you. The rehearsal process has been a really safe space to engage with a text that I don't think I'd engage with otherwise." End quote. Quote from Jillian Cicalese, Assistant Director, "We‚Äôre exploring a story that is traditionally told with cis men using a better representation of today's artists and discovering how the text translates through those voices. To me, this piece is about finding power in femininity and the relationship between daughter and father. The feminine spirit through the character of Marina brings her father back to life after years of estrangement, trials, and tribulations." End quote. Quote from Sophia Carlin, Director, ‚ÄúThe things that happen to Pericles, the loss of his wife, child, and general uncertainty of where to call home, can happen to anyone. Because we have a focus on centering marginalized voices in this production, their perspectives on these characters are upheld above anything else. My hope is that this process has become a very safe space but also a very soft space in that it is informed by the experiences and needs of the people we've chosen to collaborate with.‚Äù End Quote.

In Waiting Room Z, Shakespeare‚Äôs most often forgotten characters find themselves antsy, excited, and lost. It is here that the all-knowing Stage Manager sends them out into the world. However, it‚Äôs been years since these characters have been in the spotlight, and they‚Äôre beginning to grow impatient. Hamlet Isn't Dead's "When My Cue Comes" is a devised play that follows four of these ‚Äúleft-behind‚Äù characters in the canon and their desperate attempts to do whatever it takes to take their place on stage once again.

Helmed by @b.carty23 and devised and performed by @aaronanthonymoore @reidywatson @ladymaudlin @nataliedeboer.actor and @gabrielcethridge we are thrilled to bring this new production to @frigidnewyork 's Little Shakespeare Festival! Adaline Gomez is a NYC based actor and sad little poem writer. She has had a blast making her Hamlet Isn‚Äôt Dead debut! Stefania Gonzalez is an actress, fight choreographer, and producer living in New York City, originally from Ann Arbor, MI. Stefania Gonzalez dot com.
Audrey Loomis is a NYC based actor originally from Austin Texas. She is a graduate of the University of Texas at Austin, and her undergraduate thesis, ‚ÄúUnsex Me: Exploring Gendered Adaptation in Shakespeare‚Äù was presented at the Utah Shakespeare Festival‚Äôs Wooden O Symposium."
